The dedication dates to a period in the history of Berenike and the wider Eastern Desert that, until recently, had not been well represented. In fact, prior to excavations in the Isis temple, third-century finds from the port were relatively few, with only one inscription bearing a third-century date.
For discussion of the poor representation of the third century in Berenike, see Sidebotham 2002: 219–220, which was based on the evidence available at the time. The inscription in question, which is dated 215, was excavated in the so-called Palmyrene shrine; see A.M.F.W. Verhoogt in Sidebotham and Wendrich 1998: 193–196 (cf. SEG 48 1977 and SB 28 16916). Although not precisely dated, another inscription from the same shrine likely comes from the late 2nd or early 3rd century: see SEG 49 2117; ed. pr. of M. Dijkstra and A.M.F.W. Verhoogt in Sidebotham and Wendrich 1999: 207–218. Excavations in the temple have substantially changed this picture. As a result of them, the third century is now the second best-attested century in precisely dated inscriptions. In total, eight third-century dedications have been registered: Four of them are from the first decade of the century (years 209 and 210) and one is from 215;
Cf. preceding note for the inscription from 215; the others are BE-15 111.021.067 + 111.014.037 (inv. 111005); BE-15/18 111.040 (inv. 111007); BE-15/18 111.030 (inv. 111008); BE-22 150.032.001 (inv. 150001). the Sanskrit-Greek stele mentioned above dates to 248, and there is a dedication from the reign of Gallus and Volusianus (253);
See fn. 8 above; the inscription from 253 is BE-15/18 111.030 (inv. 111010). the inscription published here is from the period 276–281. The very latest temple inscription dates to the Tetrarchy (305).
BE-22 150.033.001 (inv. 150003). This evidence naturally changes our perspective on the period, and there can be no doubt that the port was operating throughout the third century, even if intermittently and on a smaller scale than in the first and early second centuries.
